Vladimir Putin and the risk of a Third World War
SAN FRANCISCO – Russia's invasion of Ukraine on February 24 marked the beginning of a third world war that has the potential to destroy our civilization.
The invasion was preceded by a prolonged meeting between Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping on February 4 – at the beginning of the celebrations for the Chinese Lunar New Year and the Beijing Winter Olympics.
At the end of this meeting, the two men published a carefully written 5,000-word document announcing a close partnership between their two countries.
The document is stronger than any treaty and certainly required meticulous preparatory negotiations.
I was surprised to see that Xi seems to have given Putin a free hand to invade and go to war against Ukraine.
He must be very confident and regard his confirmation as a lifetime leader of China later this year as a mere formality.
After concentrating all power in his hands, Xi carefully prepared the scenario in which he would be elevated to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
After securing Xi's support, Putin set out to realize his life's dream with incredible brutality.
As he approaches his 70th birthday, Putin believes that if he wants to leave his mark on Russian history, it is now or never.
But his conception of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
It seems he believes that the Russian people need a tsar whom they can follow blindly.
It is precisely the opposite of a democratic society—and it is a vision that distorts the Russian "soul," emotional to the point of sensitivity.
As a child, I met Russian soldiers many times when they occupied Hungary in 1945.
I learned that they were ready to share their last piece of bread with you if you asked them.
Later, at the beginning of the 1980s, I embarked on what I call my political philanthropy.
First, I created a foundation in my native Hungary, and then I actively participated in the disintegration of the Soviet empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, the disintegration had already begun.
I created a foundation in Russia, and then I did the same in each of the successor states.
In Ukraine, I created a foundation even before it became an independent country.
I also visited China in 1984, where I was the first foreigner authorized to establish a foundation (which I closed in 1989, just before the Tiananmen Square massacre).
I don't know Putin personally, but I have closely observed his rise to power, being aware of his cruelty.
He has reduced the capital of Chechnya, Grozny, to nothing. And he threatens to do the same to the capital of Ukraine, Kyiv.
Poutine was once a clever KGB operator, but it seems he has changed recently.
Having developed a fixed idea, it seems he has lost touch with reality.
He certainly misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He expected that Russian-speaking Ukrainians would welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but they turned out to be entirely in the same position as the Ukrainian-speaking population.
The Ukrainians have shown an incredibly brave resistance against an opponent that nothing seems to be able to stop.
In July 2021, Putin published a lengthy essay arguing that Russians and Ukrainians are truly one people and that Ukrainians have been misled by neo-Nazi agitators.
The first part of his argument is not without historical justification, given that Kyiv was the original seat of the Russian Orthodox Church.
But in the second part, it was Putin who was misled.
He should have been more cautious.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely during the Euromaidan protests in 2014.
The events of 2014 plunged him into a black rage.
But the Russian army made a poor showing when it was ordered to attack its Ukrainian brothers.
The entrenched corruption in the awarding of defense contracts has also played an important role in its insufficient results.
Yet, instead of blaming himself, Trudeau seems to have literally gone mad.
He decided to punish Ukraine for opposing him and seems to be acting without encountering any resistance.
He throws the entire Russian army into the battle and ignores all the rules of war, particularly by indiscriminately bombing the civilian population.
Many hospitals have been hit, and the electrical grid supplying the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian troops) has been damaged.
In the besieged Mariupol, 400,000 people were without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia might well lose the war.
The United States and the European Union are sending defensive weapons to Ukraine, and efforts are underway to purchase Russian-made MIG fighters, which Ukrainian pilots know how to fly.
That could make all the difference.
Whatever the outcome, Putin has already achieved wonders by managing to strengthen the determination and unity of the EU.
Meanwhile, Xi seems to have realized that Putin is going it alone.
On March 8, one day after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi emphasized that the friendship between China and Russia should remain "solid," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz to express his support for their efforts to restore peace.
He wished to exercise the utmost restraint in the war to avoid a humanitarian crisis.
It is far from certain that Putin will accede to Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be removed before they destroy our civilization.
